'''East Carolina University''' is a [[public education|public]], [[coeducational]], intensive [[research]] [[university]] located in [[Greenville, North Carolina|Greenville]], [[North Carolina]], [[United States]]. Named East Carolina University by statue and commenly known as '''ECU''' or '''East Carolina''', the university is the largest institute of higher learning east of [[Raleigh, North Carolina]] and the third largest university in North Carolina. With an enrollment of over 24,300 students, it is the fastest-growing campus in the [[University of North Carolina]] system.<ref>{{cite web| title = East Carolina University| work = Featured Campus Profiles| publisher = US Journal of Academics| date = June 2007| url = http://www.usjournal.com/en/students/campuses/ecu.html| accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref> 

The [[North Carolina General Assembly]] founded ECU on [[March 8]], [[1907]] as a teacher training school.  While East Carolina has historical strengths in [[education]], [[nursing]], [[business]], and [[medicine]], it offers over 100 [[Bachelor degree]] areas of study including [[mathematics]], [[hospitality management]], [[engineering]], [[construction management]], [[computer science]], [[exercise physiology]], and [[social work]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Overview| work = East Carolina University | publisher = University of North Carolina System| date = 2007| url = http://www.unconline.net/site.php?id=2923| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

== History ==
{{main|History of East Carolina University}}
[[Image:NC-Congress-ThomasJordanJarvis.jpg|thumb|left|Father of East Carolina University, [[Thomas Jordan Jarvis|Thomas Jordan (T.J.) Jarvis]]]]
Public Laws of North Carolina, 1907, Chapter 820 titled "''An Act to Stimulate High School Instruction in the Public Schools of the State and Teacher Training''" was the official law chartering '''East Carolina Teachers Training School''' (ECTTS) on [[March 8]], [[1907]] by the North Carolina General Assembly.<ref>{{cite web| title = An Act to Stimulate High School Instruction in the Public Schools of the State and Teacher Training| work = North Carolina Public Laws 1907, Chapter 820| publisher = North Carolina General Assembly| date = 1907-03-08| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/archives/pr_display.cfm?id=49| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> The chairman of its original board of trustees, [[Thomas Jordan Jarvis|Thomas Jordan (T.J.) Jarvis]], a former [[Governor of North Carolina]] now known as the "father of ECU", participated in groundbreaking ceremonies for the first buildings on [[July 2]], [[1908]] in Greenville, North Carolina and ECTTS opened its doors on [[October 5]], [[1909]].<ref>{{cite press release| title = Joyner Library exhibit features "father" of ECU| publisher = ECU - News Bureau| date = 2007| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/news/releases/2007/2/02082007ecujarvisexhibit.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref name="McLawhorn">{{cite web| last = Representatives McLawhorn, E. Warren, and Williams| title =  House Joint Resolution 460: A Joint Resolution honoring East Carolina University on the University's Centennial Anniversary| publisher = General Assembly of North Carolina| date = 2007-03-05| url = http://www.ncleg.net/Sessions/2007/Bills/House/PDF/H460v1.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> Although its purpose was to train "young white men and women", there were no male graduates until 1932.<ref>{{cite press release| title = An East Carolina Memoir by Henry C. Oglesby| publisher = Pieces of Eight| date = 1982-02-15| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/archives/pr_display.cfm?id=982| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> In 1920, ECTTS became a four-year institution and was renamed '''East Carolina Teachers College''' (ECTC); its first bachelor's degrees were awarded the following year in education.<ref name="McLawhorn"/> A [[master's degree]] program was authorized in 1929; the first such degree granted by ECTC was in 1933.<ref name="McLawhorn"/> Progress toward full college status was made in 1948 with the designation of the [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] as a liberal arts degree, and the [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] as a teaching degree.<ref>{{cite web| title = East Carolina University Timeline| work = University Archives| publisher = East Carolina University - Joyner Library| date = 2007| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/archives/timeline.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> A change of name to '''East Carolina College''' in 1951 reflected this expanded mission.<ref name="McLawhorn"/> Over the objections of [[Dan K. Moore|Governor Dan K. Moore]], who opposed the creation of a university system separate from the Consolidated University of North Carolina, ECC was made a regional university effective [[July 1]], [[1967]], and assumed its present name, '''East Carolina University'''. It did not, however, remain independent for long; on [[July 1]], [[1972]], it was incorporated into the University of North Carolina System, the successor to the Consolidated University.<ref name="McLawhorn"/> Today, ECU is the third largest university in North Carolina with 18,587 undergraduates and 5,764 gradutes, including the 290 [[Brody School of Medicine]] students. 

The University is home to many colleges including one of the top Medical Schools in the country, Brody School of Medicine and top ranked [[East Carolina University College of Education|College of Education]].<ref>{{cite web| last = U.S.News & World Report| title = Top Medical Schools - Primary care| work = America's Best Graduate Schools 2008| publisher = U.S.News & World Report| date = 2007| url = http://www.usnews.com/usnews/edu/grad/rankings/med/brief/mdprank_brief.php| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = College of Education Fact Sheet| work = East Carolina University College of Education| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2007| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-educ/admin/COEFactSheet.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> ECU is ranked one of the "Best Value Colleges" by [[The Princeton Review]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web| title = America's Best Value Colleges| publisher = The Princeton Review| date = 2007| url = http://www.princetonreview.com/college/research/bestvalue/results.asp?page=2| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref>

===Future of East Carolina===
[[Image:Pirate Statue.jpeg|150px|thumb|right|Pirate Statue at [[Dowdy-Ficklen Stadium]]. Dedicated on [[October 23]], [[1999]] by Irwin Belk.]]
====Dental School====
At the last Board of Trustees meeting, the members unanimously passed a resolution to start a Dental School.<ref>{{cite web| coauthors = Board of Trustees| title = Board of Trustees Meeting| publisher = East Carolina University| date = February 24, 2006| pages = 15-16| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/bot/upload/002%20-%20Minutes-6.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> The Dental School has also been unanimously approved by the UNC System Board of Governors.<ref>{{cite news| last = Fisher| first = Jean P.| title = ECU dental school OK'd| language = English| publisher = The News & Observer| date = 2006-11-11| url = http://www.newsobserver.com/102/story/509261.html| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Martin| first = Harold| authorlink =| coauthors =| title = Request to Establish a Doctor od Dental Surgery Degree Program at East Carolina University| work = Appendix O| publisher = University or North Carolina Board of Governers| date = 2006-11-03| url = http://intranet.northcarolina.edu/content.php/docs/bog/bogdocs/2007-01/minutes/Appendix%20O.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Doctor of Dental Surgery Degree Program at East Carolina University| work = Report of the Committee on Educational Planning, Policies, and Programs| publisher = The University of North Carolina - Board of Governors| date = 2006-11-10| url = http://intranet.northcarolina.edu/docs/bog/minutes/2006/11-10-06_minutes-open.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-10 }}</ref> The next step is legislative funding. The dental school has found opposition from many practicing dentists, with half the members of the North Carolina Dental Society opposing the move for fear of too much competition and a possible oversupply of dentists.<ref>{{cite web| title = Some dentists question proposed dental school at East Carolina| work = news article| publisher = Raleigh News & Observer| date = 2006-10-18| url = http://dwb.newsobserver.com/news/ncwire_news/story/3015840p-9435501c.html| accessdate = 2007-06-25 }}</ref>

====Dowdy-Ficklen Stadium Expansion====
[[Dowdy-Ficklen Stadium]] is in the beginning process of expansion. Depending on the July Board of Trustees Meeting, the stadium will become horseshoed in connecting the North and South side. Also at Dowdy-Ficklen, on the South side, a new press box and office complex will be built. The total height will be about six stories, with a two story press box covering the south side. The first of three phases of the North Campus Recreation Complex will be compete in 2007. North Recreation Complex is an athletic complex located on a 129&nbsp;acre parcel of land north of East Carolina Universityâs main campus. Phase one includes eight lighted fields, a golf course, a 5.6&nbsp;acre lake with a beach, sunbathing area, and a field house. The complex is located near the intersection of [[NC 33]] and [[US 264]].<ref>{{cite press release| title = North Recreation Fields Complex| publisher = Facilities Engineering and Architectural Services - East Carolina University| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/campus_operations/facilities_engineering_and_architectural_services/North-Fields-Recreation-Complex.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = ECU breaks ground on new athletic complex| language = English| publisher = ECU - News Bureau| date = 2006| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/news/releases/2006/03/032906northreccomplex.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref>

==Campus==
East Carolina is separated into three distinct campuses: Main Campus, Health Sciences Campus, and West Research Campus. It also has three libraries: J.Y. Joyner Library, The Music Library, and Laupus Library. ECU also owns a Field Station in New Holland, NC.

[[Image:ECU Cupola.gif|thumb|left|150px|The Cupola at ECU sits in the mall. It is a replica of the original that sat atop the Old Administrative Building]]
===Main===
The main campus is about 520&nbsp;acres (2.1&nbsp;kmÂ²) in an urban residential area of downtown Greenville. The 162 building on main campus comprise more than 4.7 million square feet (325,000&nbsp;mÂ²) of academic, research, and residential space.<ref>{{cite web| title = Facilities| work = Quick Facts| publisher = East Carolina University| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/mktg/points-east-quick-facts.cfm#Facilities| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> Many of the Main Campus buildings feature the [[Spanish Colonial Revival Style architecture|Spanish-Mission style]] architecture; inspiration drawn from Thomas Jarvis' time as an ambassador to Brazil.<ref>{{cite web| title = Thomas Jordan Jarvis - Father of East Carolina University| publisher = Joyner Library, East Carolina University| date = 2007| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/ncc/exhibit.cfm/| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = National Governors Association| title = North Carolina Governor Thomas Jordan Jarvis| work = Governor's Information| publisher = ''[[National Governors Association]]''| date = 2004| url = http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=eea575cbecff1110VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> He wanted to bring the unique architecture to Eastern North Carolina. On the main campus, there are 15 [[East Carolina University Residence Halls|residence halls]] which are divided into three separate neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web| authorlink = http://www.ecu.edu/studentlife/campusliving/| title = ECU Campus Living- Hall Information Chart 2007 - 2008| work = Residence Halls - Hall Comparison - 2007-2008| publisher = East Carolina University - Campus Living| date = 2007| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-studentlife/campusliving/chart0708.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The distinct feature of the main campus is the mall, which is a large tree-laden grassy area where many students go to relax. In the middle of the mall is the replica of the [[cupola]] on the old Austin (original Administrative and Classroom) building.

===Health Sciences Campus/Pitt County Memorial Hospital===
The Health Sciences campus is situated at [[Pitt County Memorial Hospital]] (PCMH). PCMH, a 745-bed flagship [[Level I Trauma Center]] facility in Greenville, serves as a [[teaching hospital|academic medical center]] for the Brody School of Medicine.<ref>{{cite web| title = Trauma and Critical Care| work = Pitt County Memorial Hospital| publisher = University Health Systenf of Eastern Carolina| date = 2005| url = http://www.uhseast.com/body.cfm?id=200#| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The University Health System also operates six additional hospitals and has affiliation agreements with six hospitals serving all of Eastern North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web| title = Our Hospitals| publisher = University Health Systems of Eastern Carolina| date = 2005| url = http://www.uhseast.com/body.cfm?id=6| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The area is about 2&nbsp;miles west of Main Campus on 205&nbsp;acres (0.8&nbsp;kmÂ²) with nearly 950,000 square feet of academic and research space in 39 buildings.<ref>{{cite web| title = Facilities| work = Quick Facts| publisher = East Carolina University| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/mktg/points-east-quick-facts.cfm#Facilities| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> Other Buildings besides PCMH include the Brody School of Medicine, the East Carolina Heart Institute (under construction), Leo Jenkins Cancer Center, and the Allied Health "Learning Village" composed of the School of Nursing, Laupus Medical Library and School of Allied Health Sciences.<ref>{{cite web| title = East Carolina Heart Institute| work = Cardiovascular Center| publisher = University Health Systems of Eastern Carolina| date = 2007| url = http://www.uhseast.com/142828.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Leo W. Jenkins Cancer Center| publisher = Leo W. Jenkins Cancer Center| date = 2007| url = http://www.leowjenkinscancercenter.org/| accessdate = 2007-06-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Spencer, PhD| first = Dorothy A. | coauthors = C. Laurence Robbs| title = The new Laupus Library: East Carolina's University's Health Sciences Division Builds a Learning Village for interdisciplinary excellence| work = The Library As Place| publisher = Association of Academic Health Sciences Libraries| date = 2003-11-05| url = http://www.aahsl.org/building/eastcarolina.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

===West Research===
West Research Campus is located about four&nbsp;miles west of the Health Sciences Campus. It is located on a 27,000-square-foot building on the former [[Voice of America]] site.<ref>{{cite web| last = Latham| first = Art| title = N.C. Agromedicine Institute obtains health research grant | work = Perspectives Online| publisher = North Carolina State University| date = 2002| url = http://www.cals.ncsu.edu/agcomm/magazine/spring02/agromed.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> It is also the site of the North Carolina Institute for Health and Safety in Agriculture, Forestry, and Fisheries with an administrative and several support buildings.<ref>{{cite web| title = Mission, Vision, Goals| publisher = North Carolina Agromedicine Institute| url = http://www.ncagromedicine.org/mission.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

===Libraries===
[[Image:sonic plaza.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Sonic Plaza and J.Y. Joyner Library]]
[http://www.ecu.edu/lib/ J.Y. Joyner Library] is located on the main campus and holds nearly 1.3 million bound volumes, 2.5 million pieces of [[microform]], 532,000 government documents, more than 24,000 journal subscriptions.<ref>{{cite web| title = About Joyner Library| publisher = J.Y. Joyner Library, East Carolina University| date = 2006-03-14| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/development/about.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> Joyner Library is located beside the ECU Mall. The [http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/music/index.cfm Music Library] is a branch of Joyner housing almost 78,000 items. It is located on the first floor of A.J. Fletcher Music Center.<ref>{{cite web| title = About the Music Library| publisher = Joyner Library, East Carolina University| date = 2006-10-06| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/music/about.cfm| accessdate = }}</ref> Lastly, there is the [http://www.ecu.edu/cs-dhs/laupuslibrary/ Laupus Library]. It holds 158,457 volumes (print and non-print) and 8,712 current print, non-print, and electronic serial titles.<ref>{{cite web| title = History of the Library| work = Laupus Library| publisher = Laupus Library| date = 2007-02-27| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-dhs/laupuslibrary/historyofthelibrary.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

===Mattamuskeet field station===
The Field Station is located in [[Hyde County, North Carolina|New Holland]], [[North Carolina]]. The area serves as a field station for the Coastal Studies, Coastal Resource Management, and Biology programs.<ref>{{cite web| title = ECU Field Station for Coastal Studies at Mattamuskeet| work = Mattamuskeet Field Station| publisher = College of Arts and Sciences - East Carolina University| date = 2001| url = http://www.artsci.ecu.edu/newmatt/Mattamuskeet.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The main goal of the Field Station is economic development into the region through both environmental education and eco-tourism.<ref>{{cite web| title = Field Station for Coastal Studies at Mattamuskeet| publisher = ICW-NET, LLC.| date = 2004| url = http://www.albemarle-nc.com/mattamuskeet/studies/| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> It is also to serve as a facility for small retreats and as a base for research on coastal issues.<ref>{{cite web| title = Mattamuskeet Field Station| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2006-09| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-acad/rgs/upload/mattstat.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> 
It is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1980.<ref>{{cite web| title = Lake Mattamuskeet Pump Station| work = NORTH CAROLINA - Hyde County| publisher = National Register of Historic Places| date = 1980| url = http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/NC/Hyde/state.html| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> It is adjacent to the 49,925&nbsp;acre [[Lake Mattamuskeet|Mattamuskeet Wildlife Refuge]].

== Colleges and schools==
ECU is home to seven colleges, two schools and one professional school. The oldest school is the modern day '''College of Education'''. 
[[Image:Flanagan Building.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Flanagan Building was built in 1939. It was funded by state and Public Works Administration funds. This was the only project on campus funded by PWA funds. The building is named for Edward Gaskill Flanagan, ECTC Board of Trustees member, and a Greenville native.<ref>{{cite web| title = Flanagan Building| publisher = Joyner Library - East Carolina University| date = 2006-02-22| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/archives/bldg_history.cfm?id=57| accessdate = 2007-06-15}}</ref>]]

The [[liberal arts]] college at East Carolina University is the '''[[Thomas Harriot College of Arts and Sciences]]'''.<ref>{{cite web| last = White| first = Alan| title = The Liberal Arts| work = Thomas Harriot College of Arts and Sciences| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2007-03-05| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-cas/liberalarts/libarts.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> It consists of 16 departments, making it the fourth largest school at East Carolina University, after the College of Education, the College of Technology and Computer Science, and the College of Fine Arts and Communication.<ref>{{cite web| title = Unduplicated Undergraduate Fall Enrollment History by Unit and Major (CIP)| work = Fact Book 2006 - 2007| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2007| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/ipre/customcf/factbook/factbook0607.pdf#page=59| format = pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The liberal arts college has its roots in the beginning of the University.<ref>{{cite web| title = Welcome to Thomas Harriot College of Arts and Sciences| work = Thomas Harriot College of Arts and Sciences| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2006-09-25| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-cas/| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

The '''[[College of Business at East Carolina University|College of Business]]''' consist of five undergraduate majors with concentrations in each, plus a [[Masters in Business Administration]] and [[Master of Science in Accounting]] program. The College beginnings come in 1936 when the Department of Commerce was organized. It then changed to a Department of Business Education, then to a Department of Business. Finally, in 1960, the School of Business was formed.<ref>{{cite press release| title = School of Business, One of Finest in the Country| publisher = ECU Report, Volume 15, No. 1| date = 1983-01| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/archives/pr_display.cfm?id=629| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The college undergraduate programs was accredited in 1967, and the graduate programs was accredited in 1976 by The [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]].<ref>{{cite web| title = College of Business Statistics| work = About the College of Business| publisher = East Carolina University - College of Business| date = 2007-03-05| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-bus/collegestatistics.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The college is a governing school of the Graduate Management Admission Council.<ref>{{cite web| title = Governing Schools| work = About Us| publisher = Graduate Management Admission Council| date = 2007| url = http://www.gmac.com/gmac/AboutUs/GoverningSchools.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

The '''College of Education''' is the oldest college at ECU. It houses and administers all of the education majors. There are 14 undergraduate majors in the College. "ECUâs College of Education prepares more professionals for North Carolina schools than any other university in the state. The College scored higher than other North Carolina universities when the state board evaluated teacher education programs last year. And, the
Institution of Higher Education Performance Report showed ECU was first in the number of graduates who were employed in public schools across the state."<ref>{{cite press release| title = College of Education 2005-2006 Fact Sheet| publisher = College of Education| date = 2006| url = http://author.ecu.edu/cs-educ/admin/upload/2005-2006%20Final%20Fact%20Sheet.pdf| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> 

The '''[[College of Fine Arts and Communication at East Carolina University|College of Fine Arts and Communication]]''' comprises four schools that range from [[dance]] to [[design]] and [[broadcast journalism]]. The college officially opened on [[July 1]], [[2003]], but can trace its roots to ECU founding; the school hired art and music professionals in 1907 to train teachers.<ref>{{cite web| title = About the College | work = ECU College of Fine Arts & Communication| publisher = College of Fine Arts & Communication| date = 2007-01-12| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-cfac/about.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

The '''[[The College of Health and Human Performance at East Carolina University|College of Health and Human Performance]]''' is made up of three departments and handles all of the Recreational and Exercise degrees at East Carolina University. It took on its name in 2003, but traces its legacy to the Department of Physical Education in 1930. It was the 1930 East Carolina Teachersâ College Planning Document number two priority. In 1938, the Department of Physical Education was established and [[Physical education|PE]] became a specialty area for high school teachers.<ref>{{cite web| title = History of the College of Health and Human Performance| publisher = The College of Health & Human Performance| date = 2007-01-11| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-hhp/upload/HHP_HX_Timeline.pdf|  accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

The '''[[The College of Human Ecology at East Carolina University|College of Human Ecology]]''' houses four departments and one school along with two institutes. It was first incorporated in 1968 and started to admit students in 1971.<ref>{{cite web| title = History| work = College of Human Ecology| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2006-09-21| url = http://www.ecu.edu/che/he/history.html| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> "''The Carolyn Freeze Baynes Institute for Social Justice'' is an international forum for addressing questions, presenting ideas, and developing innovations. The Institute's focus in these activities it the identification of injustices and development of more just alternatives through systematic professional research, scholarship, and public presentation of findings and ideas."<ref>{{cite web| title = The Carolyn Freeze Baynes Institute of Social Justice| publisher = College of Human Ecology| date = 2007-04-23| url = http://www.ecu.edu/che/he/cfbi.html| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

The '''[[College of Technology and Computer Science at East Carolina University|College of Technology and Computer Science]]''' comprises seven schools that make up the College. The college started to offer a BS in [[Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Request for Authorization to Establish a Bachelor of Science Degree in Engineering at East Carolina University| work = Appendices for the minutes on March 19, 2004 | publisher = The University of North Carolina| date = May 18, 2004| url = http://www.northcarolina.edu/content.php/bog/minutes/2004/appendixk3.htm| accessdate = June 24, 2007 }}</ref>  The college offers three other degrees along with engineering. <ref>{{cite web| title = Academic Departments| work = College of Technology and Computer Science| publisher = East Carolina University| date = September 14, 2006| url = http://www.tecs.ecu.edu/AcademicDeptments.htm| accessdate = June 24, 2007}}</ref>

The '''[http://www.ecu.edu/ah/ School of Allied Health Sciences]''' encompasses the other health science majors. The school offers over 15 majors from B.S. to PhD.  All of the health sciences majors are located in the Allied Health Sciences building which is in the West Campus beside the Brody School of Medicine. It was established in the 1967-68 school year.<ref>{{cite web| title = The School of Allied Health Sciences| publisher = East Carolina University| date = 2007-05-16| url = http://www.ecu.edu/ah/| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

The '''[http://www.nursing.ecu.edu/ School of Nursing]''' comprises one undergraduate major, Nursing. The school was created in 1959 and now offers Bachelor of Science, Masters, and PhD. The 100+ faculty teaches the students everything about the nursing field while practicing in the under served Eastern North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web| last = Brown| first = Sylvia T.| title = Welcome from the Dean| work = About us| publisher = School of Nursing| date = 2007-06-11| url = http://www.nursing.ecu.edu/about_us.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> 

The '''Brody School of Medicine''' was envisioned in the early 1960s by a group of civic leaders in Eastern North Carolina looking for a way to provide more modern medical care in the East. The School was finally established in 1974. The mission of the school set by the legislators is: "to increase the supply of primary care physicians to serve the state, to improve health status of citizens in eastern North Carolina, and to enhance the access of minority and disadvantaged students to a medical education."<ref>{{cite web| title = History: A Legacy of Commitment| work = About the School| publisher = The Brody School of Medicine at East Carolina University| date = 2007-01-15| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-dhs/med/abtHistory.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> One hundred percent of the 290 current students (to be expanded to 325 with the Fall Class of 2007) are North Carolina citizens. The School is the only school in the state that only accepts North Carolina residents.<ref>{{cite web| last = Office of Admissions| title = Selection Factors | work = Admissions| publisher = The Brody School of Medicine at East Carolina University| url = http://www.ecu.edu/bsomadmissions/application/selection_factors.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

==Greek life==
{{main|East Carolina University Greek Life}}

There are nine [[Sorority|Social Sororities]] at the East Carolina Campus,<ref>{{cite web| title = Panhellenic Council| work = Greek Life| publisher = Division of Student Life| date = 2007-06-05| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-studentlife/greek/Panhellenic-Council.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> all of which own a house located at or near 5th or 10th Street. There are currently 16 [[Fraternity|Social Fraternities]] at East Carolina.<ref>{{cite web| title = Interfraternity Council| work = Greek Life| publisher = Division of Student Life| date = 2007-06-05| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-studentlife/greek/Greek-Life-IFC.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The majority are located off of or near 5th Street or 10th Street. Of the 16 Social Fraternities, seven currently do not own a house.

[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC) has a presence on campus as well. There are four Historical Black Sororities and five Historical Black Fraternities. None of the NPHC currently own a house.<ref>{{cite web| title = National Pan-Hellenic Council| work = Greek Life| publisher = Division of Student Life| date = 2007-04-11| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-studentlife/greek/Greek-Life-NPHC.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

== Alumni Association and notable alumni ==
{{main|List of East Carolina University alumni}}

The East Carolina University Alumni Association was chartered, as the first class graduated in 1912, and now serves the over 123,000 living alumni through a variety of programs and projects.<ref>{{cite press release| title = The Association| publisher = East Carolina Alumni Association| url = http://www.piratealumni.com/ng/TopMenu/AboutUs/TheAssociation/tabid/6641/Default.aspx| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> The professional staff of nine are housed in the Taylor-Slaughter Alumni House,{{vague|the nine or the six are housed here?}} oversee both day to day operations and friend and supporter building events throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web| title = Staff Directory| publisher = East Carolina Alumni Association| url = http://www.piratealumni.com/ng/TopMenu/ContactUsStaff/StaffDirectory/tabid/6647/Default.aspx| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> A national Alumni Board of Directors, comprised of 15 members, directs the Association.<ref>{{cite web| title = Board of Directors| publisher = East Carolina Alumni Association| url = http://www.piratealumni.com/ng/TopMenu/VolunteerLeadership/BoardofDirectors/tabid/6644/Default.aspx| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> Two notable Alumni Association organizations are the ECU Ambassadors, current students who serve as the face of ECU at events, and the Magnolia Belles, a student-run a cappella group consisting of 10 talented undergraduate women.<ref>{{cite web| title = Ambassadors| publisher = East Carolina Alumni Association| url = http://www.piratealumni.com/ng/StudentPrograms/ECUAmbassadors/tabid/6418/Default.aspx| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = The Magnolia Belles| publisher = East Carolina Alumni Association| url = http://www.piratealumni.com/ng/StudentPrograms/MagnoliaBelles/tabid/6419/Default.aspx| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref>

East Carolina University has alumni in all aspects and walks of life. Teachers, such as [[Ron Clark]] have inspired students.<ref>{{cite news| last = Churchill| first = Theresa| title = Best-selling author highlights upcoming diversity conference at Richland| language = English| publisher = Herald & Review| date = 2007-06-10| url = http://www.herald-review.com/articles/2007/06/10/news/local_news/1024087.txt| accessdate = 2007-06-10 }}</ref> Entertainers such as [[Sandra Bullock]], [[Vince McMahon]], Beth Grant and Loonis McGlohon have entertained people.<ref>{{cite web| title = Sandra Bullock| publisher = IMDB| url = http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000113/bio| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Beth Grant| publisher = IMDB| url = http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0335275/bio| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Hamstra| first = Stuart V.| title = Mr. Loonis McGlohon - 1921-2002| date = 2002| url = http://www.cabarethotlineonline.com/SADNEWS/SadNews2002McGlohon.shtml| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> Politicians such as Senator [[Marc Basnight]] and [[U.S. Senator]] [[Robert Burren Morgan]] have successfully guided North Carolina and the United States.<ref>{{cite news| last = Hinton| first = Henry| title = Basnight gets honorary degree from "my university"| language = English| publisher = Bonesville.net| date = 2006-05-08| url = http://www.bonesville.net/Articles/HenryHinton/2006/05/050806_Hinton.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia| title = MORGAN, Robert Burren, (1925 - )| encyclopedia = Biographical Directory of the United States Congress| publisher = United States Government| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref>

==Athletics==
[[Image:ECU flag.gif|right|thumb|150px|ECU alternate flag logo]]
{{main|East Carolina Pirates}}
ECU's sports teams, nicknamed the ''[[ECU Pirates|Pirates]]'', compete in NCAA Division I-A as a full-member of the 12 team Conference USA. [[Terry Holland]], former [[Athletic Director]] and Head [[Basketball coach]] of the [[University of Virginia]], is the Pirate's current Athletic Director.<ref name="Conference">{{cite web| title = East Carolina| publisher = Conference USA| date = [[2007]]| url = http://conferenceusa.cstv.com/schools/ecu/c-usa-ecu-body.html| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Myatt| first = Al| title = Bingo! Search mission accomplished| publisher = Bonesville.net| date = [[2004]]| url = http://www.bonesville.net/Articles/AlMyatt/2004/09/090704_Myatt_News.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref> Facilities include the 43,000 seat [[Dowdy-Ficklen Stadium]] for football, the 8,000-seat [[Williams Arena at Minges Coliseum]] for men's and women's basketball, and the brand new [[US$]]12 million [[Clark-LeClair Stadium]], with a seating capacity of 3,000 (max capacity of 6,000+ when including outfield "Jungle" areas) for baseball. The Ward Sports Medicine building comprises 82,095 square feet (7627&nbsp;mÂ²) and houses the athletic department, Pirate Club offices and the Human Performance Laboratory. Athletes train in the Murphy Center a 52,475-square-foot edifice, housing the strength and conditioning facilities, along with banquet rooms, sport memorabilia, and an academic enhancement center. The Murphy Center was built for approximately $13 million and opened its doors to ECU student-athletes in June 2002.<ref name="Conference"/><ref>{{cite web| last = Tuttle| first = Steve| title = Building the Future| publisher = East Magazine| date = [[2006]]| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-admin/mktg/east/Campus-Expansion.cfm| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref>

== Traditions and events ==
There are 314 registered organizations that contribute to a diverse and vibrant [[student life]].<ref>{{cite web| title = East Carolina University| work = America's Best Colleges 2007| publisher = U.S.News & World Report| date = 2007| url = http://www.usnews.com/usnews/edu/college/directory/brief/drextras_2923_brief.php| accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref> Also a number of active and semi-active [[benevolent]] and [[philanthropic]] [[secret societies]] such as: "''Society of the Seven''", and "''The Order of the Cupola''" exist. 
''Barefoot on the Mall'' is held every Spring, which gathers musicians from all genres for an all day concert and features various games, rides, and food vendors.<ref>{{cite news| last = Trento| first = Adeline| title = 'Pirates Do It Barefoot' on the Mall| publisher = The East Carolinian| date = 2007-04-19| url = http://media.www.theeastcarolinian.com/media/storage/paper915/news/2007/04/19/News/pirates.Do.It.Barefoot.On.The.Mall-2851281.shtml| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref> It is held in the Mall area. ''Freeboot Friday'' are held every Friday evenings before home football games in uptown Greenville. It offers free concerts, free food, childrenâs activities, and a beer and wine garden for adults.<ref>{{cite web| title = Freeboot Friday| publisher = Uptown Greenville| date = 2007| url = http://www.uptowngreenville.com/about/what_we_do/events/Freeboot_Friday/| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref> ''The [[Billy Taylor]] Jazz Festival'' gathers musicians from all parts of the world to participate in this unique two day event.<ref>{{cite press release| title = Billy Taylor Jazz Festival| publisher = Greenville Convention and Visitors Bureau| date = 2007-03-28| url = http://www.visitgreenvillenc.com/news/article_view.asp?article_id=122| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref> ''The Purple & Gold Pigskin Pigout Party'', held each spring, is a celebration of football at East Carolina. This event features a carnival, various cooking contests, world famous bar-b-cue, a car show, a celebrity golf tournament, a parade, free live entertainment, and the annual Purple & Gold spring football game.<ref>{{cite web| title =Pirate Purple & Gold Pigskin Pig-Out Party|publisher = VisitNC.com| date = 2007| url = http://www.visitnc.com/tools_property_detail.asp?propertyid=35980| accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref>

==Administration==
[[Image:eculogo.jpg|right|100px|thumb|Logo of ECU based on the columns at Joyner Library]]
{{main|List of East Carolina University Administration}}
The current chancellor, Dr. Steven Ballard, has been in place since replacing Interim Chancellor Dr. William Shelton on [[June 1]], [[2004]].<ref>{{cite press release| title = Ballard Named Chancellor of East Carolina University| publisher = The University of North Carolina| date = March 19, 2004| url = http://www.northcarolina.edu/content.php/pres/news/releases/pr2004/20040319.htm| accessdate = 2007-06-06}}</ref> There have been six [[President|presidents]] and seven [[Chancellor|chancellors]].<ref>{{cite web| title = President/Chancellor Bios| publisher = Joyner Library - East Carolina University| date = 2006-02-22| url = http://www.ecu.edu/cs-lib/archives/pr_display.cfm?id=579| accessdate = 2007-06-11}}</ref> The chancellor has to report to the Board of Trustees. The Board of Trustees reports to the [[University of North Carolina|UNC Board of Governors]].

